script.description:
C# script code to execute OR absolute path to a .cs file. If a file path is provided (e.g., "/path/to/script.cs"), Unity will automatically detect it and read the file content. Make sure the passed in path is valid utf-8 encoded path. PREFERRED for executing existing script files. The script runs in the Unity Editor C# environment with access to UnityEngine and UnityEditor namespaces. When you need to capture a screenshot of the gameview during the execution of the script, use following methods
namespace UnityTcp.Editor.Tools
{
    public static class ManageScreenshot
    {
        public static bool BeginCapture(float scale = 1f); // Starts a new capture session and immediately grabs the first Game View frame into memory.
        public static bool CaptureFrame(); // Captures one more Game View frame into the active session's in-memory buffer.
        public static string EndCaptureToGif(string filePath, int fps = 25, int colorCount = 128); // Ends the active session, encodes all buffered frames into an animated .gif, writes it to disk.
    }
}
This is a one-off, immediate Editor automation script: it MUST finish quickly and MUST NOT wait. Never emit blocking calls: no Thread.Sleep, Thread.SpinWait, Task.Wait, Task.Result, .WaitOne() (on AutoResetEvent/ManualResetEvent/Mutex/Semaphore), and no busy-wait loops (e.g. while(cond){} with no yield) — all of these freeze the Unity main thread. Do NOT implement any delay, polling, or frame-spanning wait inside this one-off script (it is a Roslyn script, not a coroutine/IEnumerator body, so yield return / WaitForSeconds / WaitUntil do not apply here). If you need multi-frame work, a delay, polling, or a long-running task, split it into Unity builtin request/wait tools (e.g. request_* -> wait_*), repeat tool calls, or create a proper Unity script with lifecycle code instead.
